<section id="work-shift" class="px-6 py-24 md:py-36">
  <div class="mx-auto max-w-2xl">
    <p class="font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.25em] text-accent">
      <span class="text-neutral-600">02</span> What changes for you
    </p>
    <h2
      class="mt-4 text-3xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-neutral-50 sm:text-4xl"
    >
      Your work is changing
    </h2>

    <div class="mt-10 space-y-7 text-lg leading-relaxed text-neutral-300">
      <p>
        There is a reason the meta-framework story lands, and it is not just an
        analogy. The same shift is happening to how you work. In the framework
        era you were the frontend expert, deep in one repo, choosing the router
        and the component library and caring less about the backend because that
        was someone else's floor. With agents taking the lower-level
        implementation, <mark>you level up a floor</mark>. You go from
        single-repo specialist to system-level generalist: you care about the
        whole stack, you cross the frontend and backend boundaries that were
        never really meant to be walls, and you steer instead of type.
      </p>
      <p>
        Here is what that feels like in practice. You spot a bug. You do not
        know that code line by line, but you understand it at the system level:
        what it touches, why it is failing, roughly where the fix lives. Before,
        you would have delegated it to the one person who owns that code, because
        going in yourself was too much work and they would be faster anyway. Now
        you fire up an agent, work through the components with it, and steer it
        toward the fix. It figures out the details, you follow the reasoning, and
        the change lands, <mark>without handing it to anyone</mark>.
      </p>
      <p class="text-neutral-400">
        Multiply that across a team and the shape of the job moves up a level.
        Less time wiring one piece together, more time reasoning about how the
        whole system fits.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
